Intellisense for javascript does not detect simple Javascript classes.

Given this (ES6/TypeScript) class:

``` js
class Greeter {
    constructor(message) {
        this.greeting = message;
    }
    greet() {
        return "Hello, " + this.greeting;
    }
}
var greeter = new Greeter("world");
greeter. // I get intellisense here
```

If I write the same class by hand in ES5 (the code generated by TypeScript):

``` js
var Greeter = (function () {
    function Greeter(message) {
        this.greeting = message;
    }
    Greeter.prototype.greet = function () {
        return "Hello, " + this.greeting;
    };
    return Greeter;
}());

var greeter = new Greeter("world");
greeter. // no suggestion here
```

I get no intellisense. I think this pattern should be detected automatically...

